{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-04940/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-04940"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:49:40"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["full shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["high"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, pan, tilt, tracking"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["three shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman guides two visitors up a flight of stairs."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-04940","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-04940"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1/74e9e7c1-3dd4-41ac-99ad-7622fde69365","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T19:36:02.373Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The character of Barbara Rose is based on Barbara Woolworth Hutton. Known as “Poor Little Rich Girl” for the extravagant debutante ball her father, retail tycoon Frank Winfield Woolworth, threw for her during the Great Depression, Hutton would go on to marry seven times and lead a troubled life due to drinking, drugs, and husbands with ulterior motives.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1010.2261816838994,217.53669682422444,395.55922267355993,622.1877307976366"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1/1907f9d5-a811-4ea6-958e-bdb0a0178d71","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T19:36:22.955Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The character of Cal is likewise based on Barbara Hutton’s son Lance Graf von Haugwitz-Hardenberg-Reventlow, son of Hutton’s second husband, Count Kurt von Haugwitz-Hardenberg-Reventlow. According to Hutton’s biographer, C. David Haymann, the <em>New York Times</em> published an article reporting on the couple’s decision to raise Lance in London: “The Count and Countess are terrified that in the United States their baby may be kidnapped. They will make their permanent home in London. The Haugwitz-Reventlow child has not yet been named. According to the infant’s father, ‘In Denmark it is considered bad luck to think of naming the child before the mother is fully recovered from the ordeal of giving birth’” (quoted in Haymann, <em>Poor Little Rich Girl</em>, 136).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04940/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1548.8801698670607,339.36322932053173,300.95204025110775,651.7189807976367"}}}]}]}]}